import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
---

<MainLayout title="Ethical Risks & Critical Perspectives">
  <h1>V. Ethical Risks & Critical Perspectives</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-slate-500 -mt-4 mb-8 font-sans">Challenges and Concerns</p>

  <p>
    While AI offers tremendous potential for humanities research, its deployment raises significant
    ethical concerns that the scholarly community must address. A critical perspective on these
    technologies is essential for responsible adoption.
  </p>

  <h2>Training Data Bias</h2>

  <p>
    AI systems trained on existing digital archives inherit and can amplify the biases embedded
    in those collections.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Problem</strong>: Training data bias leads to "cultural flattening"</li>
    <li><strong>Manifestation</strong>: Models may perform poorly on underrepresented languages, scripts, or cultural traditions</li>
    <li><strong>Risk</strong>: AI tools may inadvertently reinforce existing gaps in archival representation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    When AI models are trained primarily on well-digitized Western European materials, they
    struggle with texts from other traditions—potentially widening rather than closing gaps
    in global humanities scholarship.
  </p>

  <h2>The Scraping Crisis</h2>

  <p>
    Cultural heritage institutions face an unprecedented challenge from AI companies' data
    collection practices.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Issue</strong>: AI bots systematically scraping GLAM (Galleries, Libraries, Archives, Museums) collections</li>
    <li><strong>Concern</strong>: Scraping continues regardless of robots.txt restrictions</li>
    <li><strong>Impact</strong>: Server overloads, bandwidth costs, and questions of consent</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Many institutions have found that AI training crawlers ignore standard web protocols designed
    to limit automated access, raising fundamental questions about consent, copyright, and the
    sustainability of open cultural heritage initiatives.
  </p>

  <h3>Implications for GLAM Institutions</h3>

  <p>
    The scraping crisis has forced many institutions to reconsider their open access policies,
    with some implementing stricter access controls that may limit legitimate research use
    alongside AI training.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-10 p-6 bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg">
    <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-slate-800 mb-2">Critical Consideration</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      The enthusiasm for AI in humanities must be tempered by attention to these structural
      concerns. Without addressing training data bias and respecting institutional boundaries,
      AI risks reproducing and amplifying existing inequities in scholarly infrastructure.
    </p>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
